{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567227"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:57:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:57:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18949"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.69,0.04,0.01,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5740"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11304"},{"type":"tags","id":"11336"},{"type":"tags","id":"11337"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare practitioners have a legal obligation to report certain types of conduct by other registered health practitioners. This requirement helps protect public safety and maintain professional standards.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a scenario which requires mandatory notification to the Medical Board?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A doctor who frequently arrives 15 minutes late for clinic appointments","A resident medical officer who arrives at work smelling of alcohol","A specialist who makes a clinical error resulting in temporary patient discomfort","A surgeon who takes three weeks of leave to receive treatment for depression","A general practitioner who begins a consensual relationship with a former patient six months after their last consultation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scenario describing a \u003Cstrong\u003Eresident medical officer who arrives at work smelling of alcohol\u003C/strong\u003E requires mandatory notification as it constitutes practicing while intoxicated, which is one of the four types of notifiable conduct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other scenarios do not meet criteria for mandatory notification:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA surgeon who takes three weeks of leave to receive treatment for depression\u003C/strong\u003E - Taking appropriate steps to manage one\u0027s health does not require notification unless it places patients at risk of substantial harm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA general practitioner who begins a consensual relationship with a former patient six months after their last consultation\u003C/strong\u003E - While this may raise ethical concerns, it does not constitute sexual misconduct as the therapeutic relationship had ended\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA specialist who makes a clinical error resulting in temporary patient discomfort\u003C/strong\u003E - Single instances of clinical error causing minor harm do not meet the threshold for notification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA doctor who frequently arrives 15 minutes late for clinic appointments\u003C/strong\u003E - While unprofessional, tardiness alone does not constitute notifiable conduct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe four categories of notifiable conduct are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPracticing while intoxicated by alcohol or drugs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESexual misconduct in connection with practice\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlacing the public at risk of substantial harm due to impairment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlacing the public at risk of substantial harm due to significant departure from accepted professional standards\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo further expand on sexual misconduct, according to Ahpra guidelines:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEngaging in sexual activity with a person formerly under a practitioner\u2019s care after the professional relationship has ended may also be sexual misconduct. This depends on:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ewhether the patient or client is vulnerable because of age, capacity or health conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe means by which sexual activity was established (for example, whether a practitioner used information obtained during a treating relationship to contact a patient and commence sexual activity)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe extent of the professional relationship (for example, a one-off treatment compared to a long-term program of treatment), and\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe length of time since the practitioner\u2013patient/client relationship ended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, provided that the therapeutic relationship has terminated, care has been referred elsewhere appropriately, both individuals consent, the patient is not vulnerable, and there were no suspicious circumstances surrounding the onset of sexual activity, it is unlikely to be classified as sexual misconduct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Notifiable conduct includes practicing while intoxicated by alcohol or drugs.","Sexual misconduct with a patient constitutes notifiable conduct.","Placing the public at risk of substantial harm due to impairment or deficient practice is notifiable conduct.","Having a health condition that impairs practice requires notification only if it places patients at risk of substantial harm."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","https://www.ahpra.gov.au/Notifications/mandatorynotifications/Mandatory-notifications.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T20:36:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T20:36:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11683"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attri